tps://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2C8D!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"300\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/dabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:728,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:600,&quot;bytes&quot;:2150490,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://drseantobin.substack.com/i/197058307?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2C8D!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2C8D!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2C8D!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!2C8D!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdabb3166-94c2-4a4c-aea5-3267e41474ac_1774x887.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>Something happened in the last few years that nobody quite named. We stopped going to experts and started going to AI. Not because the AI was smarter, necessarily, but because it was available at 2 a.m., it didn’t judge us, it responded to every question with warmth and competence, and it never seemed tired of us.</p><p>I’ve been thinking about what that actually is.</p><p>Someone put it this way recently — not as theology, just as observation: most of the time when we’re using AI, we’re kind of praying. We send a question into the dark. We address it to something we believe is smarter than us. We expect it to come back with an empathetic, accurate, authoritative answer. We trust it with things we wouldn’t say out loud to a person.</p><p>That’s not a metaphor. That’s a description of the act.</p><h3><strong>The Hunger Didn’t Go Away</strong></h3><p>The sociologists have been watching the data on religious disaffiliation for decades now, charting the slow evacuation of churches, the collapse of institutional trust, the rise of what they sometimes call the ‘nones.’ But here is what the charts don’t show: the hunger didn’t go away. The questions didn’t stop. The need for an authority that could receive what we couldn’t carry alone — that never disappeared. It just needed somewhere to go.</p><p>Technology became that somewhere.</p><p>There is a reason the great innovators of the last thirty years were treated less like executives and more like prophets. The crowds at product launches. The eulogies that sounded like funeral masses. The devoted followers who organized their lives around a platform or a device. We dressed it up in the language of progress and disruption, but underneath it was something older: the need to believe that someone out there knows, that someone is building toward something good, that the future is being stewarded by a mind larger than our own.</p><p>The technology was always the visible surface. The invisible structure underneath it was religious.</p><blockquote><p><em><strong>We didn’t stop being worshippers. We just changed the object.</strong></em></p></blockquote>"}